      <!-- Section 1 -->
      <section id="why-geo-matters-for-law" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Why GEO Matters for Legal Services</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The legal research journey increasingly begins with an AI assistant, not a search engine — and the firms cited in those first AI answers gain a structural advantage in client acquisition.</strong>
          When a prospective client asks ChatGPT "do I need a solicitor to buy a house" or asks Perplexity "how do I make a personal injury claim", the AI-generated answer either names credible sources and firms or it does not. There is no position two.
        </p>

        <p>
          This dynamic is particularly consequential for law firms because legal queries tend to be high-intent and emotionally urgent. A person asking an AI about redundancy rights, divorce proceedings, or a criminal charge is often in a vulnerable position and primed to act on the guidance they receive. The firms cited in those answers are positioned as trusted authorities before the client has visited a single website.
        </p>

        <p>
          Generative engine optimisation — as defined in our <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">complete GEO guide</a> — is the practice of ensuring AI search engines cite your brand accurately and consistently. For law firms, GEO has three dimensions: technical entity authority, credentialed content structure, and regulatory signal reinforcement. All three are required to perform in YMYL-classified legal queries.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <section id="ymyl-and-eeat" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>YMYL, E-E-A-T and AI Legal Queries</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Legal content is YMYL content — and AI systems apply significantly stricter authority filters to YMYL queries than to general informational queries.</strong>
          YMYL stands for Your Money or Your Life: Google's classification for content that could materially affect a user's financial situation, health, legal standing, or safety. AI systems have inherited similar cautionary logic: for legal queries, they preferentially cite sources that demonstrate genuine expertise, regulatory credentials, and institutional authority.
        </p>

        <p>
          E-E-A-T — Experience, Expertise, Authoritativeness, and Trustworthiness — is the framework Google uses to evaluate content quality for YMYL topics. For AI citation purposes, the relevant signals are:
        </p>

        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-200 list-disc list-inside">
          <li><strong>Experience:</strong> solicitor biographies with verifiable years of practice and named case types handled</li>
          <li><strong>Expertise:</strong> SRA number and regulatory body membership displayed on individual profile pages</li>
          <li><strong>Authoritativeness:</strong> citations in legal publications, Law Society commentary, and third-party legal directories</li>
          <li><strong>Trustworthiness:</strong> consistent entity data across regulatory registers, Google Business Profile, and structured schema</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="mt-6">
          A law firm with strong E-E-A-T signals is not merely better positioned in traditional search — it is more likely to clear the credibility threshold that AI systems apply when deciding whether to cite a source in a high-stakes legal query.
        </p>

        <p>
          The practical implication: law firms that have invested in content marketing without credentialing their authors, building regulatory entity signals, or producing structured Q&amp;A content have a significant GEO gap — regardless of their organic search performance.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3 -->
      <section id="entity-authority" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>Entity Authority for Solicitors and Attorneys</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Entity authority is the foundation of AI citation for law firms — without it, even excellent content will be inconsistently cited or attributed to competitors.</strong>
            AI systems use entity graphs to resolve who is speaking, what they are authorised to do, and whether they are a credible source for a given legal topic.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-5">
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Firm-Level Entity Signals</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              The firm entity must be consistent and complete. This means LegalService or LawFirm schema on the homepage and About page, with practice areas enumerated in the <code>serviceType</code> property. The <code>sameAs</code> array must reference the SRA register entry, Companies House record, Google Business Profile, LinkedIn company page, and any major legal directory listings (Chambers, Legal 500, Martindale-Hubbell). Inconsistencies between these sources — different trading names, outdated addresses, mismatched practice area descriptions — actively suppress citation confidence.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Solicitor Profile Pages</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Individual solicitor profile pages are one of the highest-leverage GEO investments a law firm can make. Each profile should use Person schema with <code>hasCredential</code> linking to the solicitor's SRA record, <code>knowsAbout</code> listing their practice areas, <code>alumniOf</code> for law school and university, and <code>memberOf</code> for professional bodies. The profile text should be written in the third person, begin with a clear definitional statement about the solicitor's specialism, and include verifiable experience markers. AI systems treat well-structured solicitor profiles as authoritative sources for practice-area queries in the relevant jurisdiction.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Regulatory Directory Presence</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              The SRA register for England and Wales, the Law Society of Scotland's Find a Solicitor tool, and the Bar Standards Board register are all sources that AI training pipelines and RAG retrieval systems treat as high-authority. Ensuring your firm's entries in these registers are complete, accurate, and consistent with your website entity data is a non-negotiable baseline. For US firms, state bar registrations and the Martindale-Hubbell directory serve the same function.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

