                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-ink-300">"Do I need a solicitor for a motoring offence"</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-ink-300">Clear recommendation + next steps</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-accent-400">High</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p class="mt-6">
          The queries with the highest GEO priority share a common characteristic: the user needs a clear, authoritative answer quickly. AI systems fill this need by citing the most credible, clearly structured source available. Law firms that produce content optimised for citability in these high-intent moments own the first touchpoint in the client acquisition journey.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5 -->
      <section id="content-strategy" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Citation-Ready Content Strategy for Law Firms</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Citation-ready legal content combines practitioner authority, clear definitional structure, and explicit Q&amp;A patterns that AI systems can extract and reproduce with confidence.</strong>
          The content strategy for legal GEO has three tiers.
        </p>

        <h3>Tier 1: Practice Area Pillar Pages</h3>
        <p>
          Each practice area — family law, employment, commercial property, wills and probate, personal injury — should have a dedicated pillar page that defines the practice area authoritatively, explains the firm's approach, and links to supporting content covering specific query types. The page should be authored by or attributed to a named solicitor with a linked profile page, and include Article schema with the solicitor's entity reference in the <code>author</code> property.
        </p>

        <h3>Tier 2: Procedural and Rights Guides</h3>
        <p>
          Supporting pages should address the specific procedural and rights-based queries that prospective clients submit to AI systems. Each page must open with a bold, definitive statement — for example: "In England and Wales, employees are entitled to statutory redundancy pay after two years of continuous service." This gives AI systems an extractable fact with a clear jurisdictional scope. Every guide should include a FAQPage schema section with at least four self-contained Q&amp;As.
        </p>

        <h3>Tier 3: Jurisdiction and Credential Signals</h3>
        <p>
          AI systems are sensitive to jurisdictional accuracy in legal content. Content that explicitly states its jurisdiction — England and Wales, Scotland, US federal vs state — is treated as more authoritative than content that omits this context. Every legal content page should state its jurisdiction clearly in the first paragraph and in the article's <code>areaServed</code> schema property.
        </p>

        <p>
          For a broader view of how to build citability into content, the <a href="/ai-brand-visibility/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AI brand visibility guide</a> covers the universal content patterns that drive AI citation across all sectors.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6 -->
      <section id="schema-markup" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Schema Markup for Law Firms</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Structured data is the machine-readable credentialing layer that allows AI retrieval systems to verify that a law firm is a legitimate, qualified source for legal content.</strong>
          Schema markup does not guarantee citation, but its absence creates ambiguity that actively suppresses it.
        </p>

        <p>
          The core schema types for law firms are:
        </p>

        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-200 list-disc list-inside">
          <li><strong>LegalService</strong> (subtype of LocalBusiness): firm homepage and contact page; include <code>areaServed</code>, <code>serviceType</code> listing all practice areas, and a complete <code>sameAs</code> array</li>
          <li><strong>Person</strong> with <code>hasCredential</code>: individual solicitor profiles; reference SRA number and qualification year</li>
          <li><strong>Article</strong> with <code>author</code> entity reference: all practice area guides and legal explainers</li>
          <li><strong>FAQPage</strong>: all content pages containing question-and-answer sections</li>
          <li><strong>BreadcrumbList</strong>: all pages below the homepage, enabling AI systems to understand the site's topical hierarchy</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="mt-6">
          All schema should be implemented in JSON-LD format, consistent with the structured data standards described in our <a href="/geo-services/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO services overview</a>. Avoid Microdata or RDFa implementations — JSON-LD is the format that modern AI retrieval systems parse most reliably.
        </p>
